articles.description:
SAN FRANCISCO, USA, Nov 09 (IPS) - The governments of Israel and the United States are now in disagreement over how many Palestinian civilians it’s okay to kill. Last week -- as the death toll from massive Israeli bombardment of Gaza neared 10,000 people, including several thousand children -- top U.S. officials began to worry about the rising horrified outcry at home and abroad. So, they went public with muted misgivings and calls for a “humanitarian pause.” But Israel’s Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu made clear that he would have none of it.

Read the full story, “Israels Military Is Part of the U.S. War Machine”, on globalissues.org →
articles.title: Israels Military Is Part of the U.S. War Machine

articles.description:
PURI, India, Nov 07 (IPS) - For more than 33 years, a group of strong-willed women from the village of Tandahara, India have kept their homes and village safe and plan to continue despite the unrelenting impacts of increasingly severe monsoons.  The sun is high in the noon sky—humidity unrelenting at 95 percent in this Indian sea-coast village. The monsoon has been deficient; rice paddies are yellowing on the edges from the salty surf misting in on them. Waves now break barely 200 metres from the farms and homes.

Read the full story, “The Relentless Struggles of India's Seawall Mammas”, on globalissues.org →
articles.title: The Relentless Struggles of India's Seawall Mammas

articles.description: Surgeons at NYU Langone Health in New York have successfully performed the world's first complete human eye transplant on a patient named Aaron James. The procedure, which took place in May, aims to enhance the overall cosmetic outcome by providing support to the transplanted eye socket and lid. While the patient's vision outcome remains uncertain, the transplanted eye appears healthy, marking a significant advancement in the field of medical innovation. This surgery provides scientists with an extraordinary opportunity to study and understand the healing process of the human eye.
articles.title: New York surgeons perform world's first human eyeball transplant

articles.description: Steve Bannon, former senior adviser to Donald Trump, appealed his criminal conviction for defying a subpoena from a congressional panel investigating the Capitol attack. Bannon argued that he did not receive a fair trial because the judge barred him from making arguments central to his defense, including his claim that he did not have to comply with the subpoena due to executive privilege. However, the appeals court appeared skeptical of his argument, noting that much of the information sought by the committee was unrelated to his interactions with Trump.
articles.title: Donald Trump ally Steve Bannon faces skeptical court in bid to overturn contempt conviction

articles.description: Two 18-year-olds, Charlotte Wimer and Gray Segal, were arrested in New York for tearing down posters depicting Israeli hostages kidnapped by Hamas. The incident took place outside a private property in Gramercy Park. The two individuals have been charged with criminal mischief. The torn-down posters have been replaced with new ones, featuring images of the 240 hostages taken by the terror group. This act of vandalizing or removing the posters has been condemned as antisemitic and inhumane.
articles.title: Two 18-year-olds arrested after tearing down Hamas hostages posters in New York

articles.description: Seven detectives from the Nashville police department have been suspended after writings by a killer were leaked online. The detectives have been placed on administrative assignment to investigate how conservative commentator Steven Crowder obtained the documents. The move is said to be to protect the integrity of the ongoing investigation and is not punitive.
articles.title: US: Nashville police suspends 7 detectives after school shooter's writings leaked

articles.author: Raj Shekhar
articles.description: A top Lashkar-e-Taiba commander, Akram Ghazi, was shot dead in Pakistan, making it the second assassination of a terrorist targeting India in one week. Ghazi was responsible for recruiting terrorists for Lashkar and played a role in radicalizing individuals who infiltrated into Kashmir. Pakistani agencies are investigating the killing and are considering local rivals and internal conflicts within Lashkar as possible motives. This killing adds to a series of recent setbacks for Lashkar and its parent organization, ISI.
articles.title: Key LeT commander killed by unidentified men in Pakistan

articles.description: Violence and fighting have escalated in Sudan, particularly in the capital and in the western region of Darfur. Witnesses report seeing corpses in the streets, and there are concerns about ethnically motivated mass killings. The Rapid Support Forces (RSF) and the Sudanese army are battling for control, with the RSF claiming control of all but one major city in Darfur. There have been reports of serious human rights abuses by the RSF and affiliated militias, and the US embassy in Khartoum has expressed deep concern.
articles.title: Bodies litter streets as fighting intensifies in Sudan

articles.description: Greece's state ombudsman is launching an independent investigation into the coast guard's handling of a maritime tragedy in June. The incident involved an overloaded boat carrying migrants trying to reach Europe, with hundreds feared to have drowned. The ombudsman's decision comes after the Greek coast guard denied initiating a disciplinary investigation. A military court is already conducting a preliminary investigation into the shipwreck, which resulted in 104 survivors and 78 bodies being recovered.
articles.title: Independent inquiry launched into shipwreck off Greece that left hundreds of migrants feared dead

articles.description: US stock markets remained steady as investors awaited signals from the Federal Reserve regarding US interest rates. European indices, on the other hand, closed the day with solid gains. Oil prices rebounded slightly but had minimal impact on the recent losses due to slowing demand expectations and reduced fears of a broader conflict in the Middle East.
articles.title: US stocks pause for breath as traders await Fed guidance

articles.description: Israel has agreed to implement four-hour daily humanitarian pauses in its offensive against Hamas in northern Gaza, according to the White House. President Joe Biden had urged Israel for a multi-day stoppage in the fighting to secure the release of hostages held by Hamas. While a formal cease-fire is not currently possible, Biden requested a pause of at least three days for negotiations. Israel will also open a second corridor for civilians to flee the conflict areas.
articles.title: Israel agrees to 4-hour daily pauses in Gaza fighting to allow civilians to flee, White House says

articles.description: The shortage of lamination paper in Pakistan is causing delays in issuing new passports, leading to difficulties for citizens. The paper used for passports is imported from France, and the limited supply is causing a backlog in processing applications. Many individuals, including students and those planning to travel for work or leisure, are being affected by the delays. The government has assured that the situation will soon be under control, but there is skepticism among the public.
articles.title: Pakistan running out of lamination paper, unable to print passports

articles.description: Germany commemorated the 85th anniversary of Kristallnacht, or the "Night of Broken Glass," in which the Nazis terrorized Jews throughout the country. Chancellor Olaf Scholz and Jewish leader Josef Schuster spoke at an anniversary ceremony in Berlin and condemned the discrimination and antisemitism that still exists in Germany. The commemoration comes at a time when antisemitism is on the rise in Germany and across Europe, with many Jews living in fear and facing discrimination.
articles.title: Germans commemorate 'Night of Broken Glass' terror as antisemitism is on the rise again

articles.description: Spanish right-wing politician Alejandro Vidal-Quadras has been shot in the face on a street in Madrid. The 78-year-old, a former member of Spain's conservative Popular Party and a founder of the far-right Vox party, was conscious when taken to the hospital. Police are investigating the shooting, and no arrests have been made. Vox President Santiago Abascal stated that Vidal-Quadras' life is not in immediate danger.
articles.title: Spanish conservative politician shot in face in Madrid. Gunman escaped on a motorbike, reports

articles.description: CIA Director Bill Burns and David Barnea, who heads Israel's Mossad spy agency, are currently in Doha for trilateral discussions with Qatari officials. The talks aim to formulate a plan for a potential humanitarian ceasefire in Gaza, which would involve the release of hostages and the distribution of additional aid to the region.
articles.title: Israeli, US spy chiefs in Doha talks on Gaza humanitarian pause: official

articles.description: Russia has expressed shock at the Israeli ambassador's statement that it could take up to two weeks to evacuate Russian citizens from the Gaza Strip. The Russian foreign ministry spokeswoman called the logic unacceptable and stated that Russia had followed all the necessary procedures for submitting evacuation lists. Over 500 Russian citizens, including 300 minors, are waiting to be evacuated from the blockade in Gaza. No Russians have been confirmed as having left Gaza since the reopening of the Rafah checkpoint on November 1.
articles.title: Moscow 'shocked' by timeline to evacuate Russians from Gaza

articles.description: Israel's army is using data from carrion-eating birds to locate corpses from the October 7 attack by Hamas militants. Eagles, vultures, and other birds of prey fitted with tracking devices have been assisting in the search for human remains. The birds are part of a program that tracks their migratory patterns, feeding habits, and environmental threats.
articles.title: Birds of prey help Israel search for Hamas attack victims

articles.description: A banner asking residents to clean up after Diwali celebrations in Singapore will be taken down to avoid misunderstanding, according to a parliamentarian. The banner was put up by the Mountbatten Residents' Network to address the issue of litter left behind after the festival. However, it was misconstrued as targeting a particular race. Another banner with a festive message will remain.
articles.title: Lawmaker intervenes after banner asked Indians to clean up rubbish after Diwali celebrations in Singapore

articles.description: During a UN review of Germany's human rights record, several Muslim countries criticized Germany's support for Israel and its bans on pro-Palestinian protests. However, Germany received overall praise for its robust human rights record. The war in Gaza was a major point of contention, with countries like Egypt, Jordan, and Turkey criticizing Germany's position. Germany reiterated Israel's right to defend itself and expressed concern over rising anti-Semitic acts.
articles.title: Germany criticised at UN over Gaza war stance

articles.description: The heads of the CIA and Mossad met with the Qatari prime minister in Doha to discuss a potential deal for hostage releases and a temporary ceasefire between Hamas and Israel in Gaza. Qatar has been leading mediation efforts between the two sides. The outcome of the meeting is unknown. The talks also included discussions on allowing humanitarian fuel imports into Gaza. Qatari Emir Sheikh Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani later traveled to the UAE, where he met with the Emirati president, though the purpose of the visit is unclear.
articles.title: Mossad, CIA chiefs meet Qatar PM in Doha on Gaza hostage deal: Source

articles.description: The Biden administration is appealing a judge's decision to block a rule imposing new restrictions on asylum seekers at the US-Mexico border. The rule, which aims to limit asylum for migrants who entered the US illegally or passed through other nations without seeking protection, was deemed to violate federal immigration law. The government argues that the rule includes exceptions and is therefore valid. Immigrant advocacy groups represented by the ACLU challenged the rule.
articles.title: Biden administration urges US court to uphold asylum restrictions

articles.description: China and the United States engaged in arms control talks in Washington this week, marking the first such meeting since the Obama administration. While the discussions were described as constructive, no follow-up meeting has been scheduled. The talks aim to set a positive tone ahead of a possible meeting between Presidents Joe Biden and Xi Jinping next week. The US is concerned about China's nuclear arsenal expansion, but China did not provide substantive responses to US requests for transparency on its nuclear forces.
articles.title: US says China reveals little in arms control talks

articles.description: Starting from Wednesday, a ban on the recreational use and possession of nitrous oxide, commonly known as 'laughing gas', will be in effect in Britain. The government cited the drug's contribution to anti-social behavior and health hazards as reasons for the ban. Offenders could face fines or up to two years in prison, and the maximum punishment for dealing the drug has been doubled to 14 years. Nitrous oxide is the third most commonly used drug by 16 to 24-year-olds and can lead to anaemia, nerve damage, or paralysis with heavy use.
articles.title: Britain bans 'laughing gas' to curb anti-social behaviour

articles.description: Vivek Ramaswamy, a Republican presidential candidate, stated that he would withdraw the United States from the Paris climate accord if elected. He believes that the climate change agenda is a hoax and that global warming is not an existential risk. Ramaswamy argues that the US should not be part of the Paris agreement and that policies restricting fossil fuel usage are more harmful to humans than climate change itself. He also emphasized the importance of focusing on domestic policies rather than being the "global police.
articles.title: Republican climate skeptic Ramaswamy to quit Paris deal if elected

articles.description: Turkish parliament has reportedly removed Coca-Cola and Nestle products from its restaurants citing their alleged support for Israel. However, there was no clear indication of how these companies showed their support for Israel's war effort. Last month, Nestle had temporarily closed one of its production plants in Israel as a precautionary measure, making it the first consumer products giant to respond to the ongoing conflict.
articles.title: Turkey House bans Coke, Nestle from its eateries over Gaza

articles.description: The Secretary-General of the United Nations, Antonio Guterres, announced on Monday that during the month-long conflict between Israel and Hamas, 89 UNRWA employees who were providing aid to Palestinian refugees in Gaza were killed. Guterres stated that this is the highest number of casualties ever recorded among UNRWA staff during a similar period. He further added that many of these workers lost their lives along with their family members.
articles.title: With 89 staffers dead, Gaza war turns out to be deadliest for UN

articles.description: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu stated that Israel would consider temporary halts in the fighting in Gaza to allow humanitarian aid to enter or to permit the release of hostages held by Hamas militants. However, Netanyahu maintained that Israel would not agree to a ceasefire unless all individuals held captive in the Hamas-controlled Palestinian territory were released.
articles.title: Israel open to 'little pauses' in Gaza fighting, says Netanyahu

articles.description: Pakistan Muslim League Nawaz (PML-N) and a Karachi-based party, Muttahida Qaumi Movement Pakistan (MQM-P), have declared that they will be jointly participating in the upcoming general elections scheduled on February 8. The MQM-P delegation had a meeting with the PML-N leader Nawaz Sharif at the party's Model Town secretariat in Lahore, which led to this development.
articles.title: PML-N, MQM-P to contest February 8 polls jointly in Pakistan

articles.description: A shark pup has been born through parthenogenesis at Brookfield Zoo near Chicago. The baby epaulette shark hatched during the summer, and its mother has never shared a tank with a male. Parthenogenesis is a form of asexual reproduction. The birth adds to the zoo's diversity of life. The shark pup is currently two months old and measures approximately 6 inches. It has been eating well and will soon be visible to zoo visitors.In contrast, the epaulette shark pup has fared better and has recently made its public debut, captivating visitors in the zoo's Living Coast exhibit.
articles.title: Brookfield zoo celebrates birth of shark pup through parthenogenesis

articles.description: Representative Marjorie Taylor Greene has admitted that Republicans prioritize media appearances and online discussions over actual work. She also expressed frustration with Republicans in Congress for not holding the government accountable. However, her own priorities have been questioned as she focuses on censuring Representative Rashida Tlaib instead of addressing the impending government shutdown. Greene's initial censure resolution was unsupported and now a revised resolution is set to be voted on. Meanwhile, other House Republicans are focusing on spending bills.
articles.title: Marjorie Taylor Greene criticizes Republicans' focus on media over accountability

articles.description: American YouTuber MrBeast's video about constructing 100 wells in Africa has received mixed responses. Kenyan activists and journalists pointed out the failures of the Kenyan government. Despite potential backlash, MrBeast believes the wells will provide clean drinking water for 500,000 people in Cameroon, Kenya, Somalia, Uganda, and Zimbabwe. The associated fundraising campaign has raised over $300,000. MrBeast also donated supplies to Kenyan schools and built a bridge and donated bicycles to Zimbabwean villages.
articles.title: American youtuber MrBeast's Africa well-drilling video sparks debate

articles.description: The European Space Agency (ESA) is organizing a competition to develop a robotic cargo capsule for transportation to and from the International Space Station (ISS). The capsule will be operated as a commercial venture by the competition winner, who will receive financial support and technical assistance from ESA. The selected company may also be tasked with upgrading the capsule for transporting ESA astronauts and potentially traveling to other destinations, such as the Moon. This competition model is inspired by NASA's successful approach of working with private companies.
articles.title: European space agency to develop commercial cargo capsule

articles.description: A fire in an informal immigrant neighborhood in Coronel, Chile, resulted in the death of 14 individuals, most of whom were children. The victims are believed to be undocumented Venezuelan immigrants who had recently arrived in the area. The cause of the fire is still being determined, but preliminary reports suggest that it may have been sparked by a fire from a handmade stove. Chilean President Gabriel Boric expressed his condolences and called for reflection on how society treats immigrants.
articles.title: Fire in Chile immigrant neighborhood kills 14, including eight children

articles.description: Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio Costa has announced his resignation following his involvement in a corruption probe. Costa's chief of staff was arrested earlier in the day as part of the investigation, which focuses on alleged malfeasance, corruption, and influence peddling relating to lithium mine concessions and green energy projects. Costa, who has been the country's Socialist leader since 2015, defended his innocence and expressed his trust in the justice system.
articles.title: Portuguese prime minister resigns after being caught up in corruption probe

articles.description: Ukraine's President Volodymyr Zelenskiy has proposed extending an export ban on Ukrainian natural gas for the whole of 2024, a presidential decree said on Tuesday. The export ban was introduced soon after Russia's full-scale invasion of Ukraine in February 2022 and was then extended to cover 2023. The decree also urged the government to increase the capacity of Ukraine's gas transmission system "to ensure the import of natural gas and its accumulation in underground gas storage facilities".
articles.title: Zelenskiy proposes extending Ukraine's gas export ban

articles.description: Houston Texans rookie quarterback CJ Stroud, after leading his team to victory against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, used his post-game press conference to draw attention to his incarcerated father. Stroud expressed the challenges of balancing his role as a family man, a football player, and helping his father, who is serving a 38-year to life sentence. He highlighted the need for criminal justice reform and the deplorable conditions in some prisons, emphasizing the importance of treating prisoners as humans. Stroud hopes his father will one day be able to attend his games.
articles.title: US 'Criminal justice system is corrupt' says footballer CJ Stroud

articles.description: Former Israeli Prime Minister Naftali Bennett engaged in a discussion with MSNBC host Katy Tur and the international community regarding the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. Many global community members criticized Israel's response to the recent Hamas attack, accusing them of excessive force and even genocide. Bennett argued that Israel is held to a different standard and posed a hypothetical scenario to highlight this point. He opposed a two-state solution and claimed that Israel had previously given Gaza to the Palestinians, but they used it to attack Israel instead.
articles.title: ​Former Israeli PM Naftali Bennett defends Israel's actions amidst international criticism

articles.description:
Buildings destroyed after the earthquake on February 13, 2023, in Hatay, Turkey. | Murat Saka/dia images via Getty Images
    

  
Turkey is investigating and has arrested some contractors, but the entire political and economic system is implicated.
 Turkey is still in the middle of an emergency, reeling from the earthquake that killed at least 35,000 people last week. But the finger-pointing has already begun. 
The rush to punishment comes amid the grief, but also the mounting fury and frustration over the Turkish government’s earthquake response. Much of that is focused on the emergency response — waiting for aid and rescue teams — but it is also extending to anger about policies before the earthquake, about how shoddy building construction may have exacerbated the devastation of the dis…
articles.title: Who is responsible for Turkey’s bad buildings?

articles.description:
Getty Images
    

  
How we turned 20,000 Soviet nukes into zero-carbon energy — and how we can do the same with some of our own.
 Just a decade ago, one in 10 American lightbulbs was powered by dismantled Russian nuclear weapons.
That was made possible by the Megatons to Megawatts program, an agreement negotiated after the collapse of the Soviet Union to convert uranium from Russia’s nuclear weapons stockpile into fuel for US nuclear power plants. The unconventional policy was first proposed by MIT physicist Thomas Neff in a 1991 New York Times op-ed. By the time Megatons to Megawatts ran its full course from 1993 to 2013, it had eliminated about 20,000 nuclear warheads and stood out as a point of shared pride in the often jaded arms control and disarmament field. “Nearly every commercia…
articles.title: 10 years ago, we were turning nuclear bombs into nuclear energy. We can do it again.

articles.description:
Volunteers stand on rubble of a destroyed building in Kahramanmaras, Turkey, on February 7, 2023. | Adem Altan/AFP via Getty Images
    

  
What Turkey and Syria’s deadly earthquakes reveal about wealth.
 In the early hours of Monday, February 6, residents living in southern Turkey and northern Syria were woken by violent shaking, collapsing buildings, and sweeping blackouts. The earthquake buried residents in rubble and was followed by powerful aftershocks. By the following Monday, the death toll had passed 36,000 people. “It was like the apocalypse,” Abdul Salam al-Mahmoud, a resident of Atareb, Syria, told Reuters.  
The country is no stranger to quakes, having lost 17,000 people to a 7.4-magnitude tremor in 1999. But while last week’s earthquake was a 7.8-magnitude quake, and had an u…
articles.title: Why earthquakes are deadlier depending on where you live

articles.description:
A suspected Chinese spy balloon flies above Charlotte, North Carolina, on February 4, 2023.  | Peter Zay/Anadolu Agency via Getty Images
    

  
As all these objects fall, a new space race is rising.
 Now that the US military has shot down a suspected spy balloon from China and three other unidentified flying objects, there will be debates about the UFOs’ meaning, their capabilities, and why they were all up there in the first place. 
Though former CIA Director Michael Hayden said the initial balloon’s threat to the welfare of Americans was vastly inflated, others described the incident as a wake-up call. Former Trump national security adviser H.R. McMaster hopes it will lead to a “Sputnik moment,” harkening back to the US space race with the Soviet Union. The Wall Street Journal even war…
articles.title: Why the balloon and UFO affairs are a Sputnik moment

articles.author: M.L. Nestel
articles.description:
She tried to censure and it came up short. 
Now she's shaming the names who didn't vote in favor. 
Rep. Marjorie Taylor Greene (R-GA) had willed a resolution to censure Rep. Rashida Tlaib (D-MI) for her attendance of a protest opposing the war in Gaza. 
POLL: Should Trump be allowed to run for office?
"List of feckless Republicans that voted WITH Democrats to table my censure resolution against Rashida Tlaib," Greene said on Wednesday. "This is why Republicans NEVER do anything to stop the communists Democrats or ever hold anyone accountable!! PATHETIC."

She created a social media thread naming some of her friends in the House who didn't have what it took to vote with her. 
They include current House Speaker Mike Johnson, Rep. Chip Roy (R-TX), and Rep. Ken Buck (R-CO) who announced he wasn't running for reelection. 

	Earlier in the week, Greene preemptively lashed out after learning that her effort wasn't gaining a coalition in Congress.
"I want to remind you, this happened on the same day Hezbollah declared a day of immense anger," she said. "And Rashida Tlaib organized with that group. And they did. They did protest, and they did an insurrection into our Capitol complex, stopping Congress and stopping the Senate."
The media was quick to take notice of the lawmaker's swing and miss Wednesday.
"Colleague Kelly Phares rpts 23 GOPers join Dems to table or kill effort to censure Dem MI Rep Tlaib," tweeted Chat Pergram.
Melanie Zanona also tweeted: "motion to table — aka kill — MTG’s resolution to censure Rep. Rashida Tlaib just passed the House, with help of 23 Republicans."

And CNN's Manu Raju added that the effort to take on Tlaib quickly died tweeting: "House kills resolution to censure Rashida Tlaib. 23 Republicans voted with Dems. MTG offered the resolution."
articles.title: 'Pathetic': Marjorie Taylor Greene attacks 'feckless Republicans' who voted against her

articles.author: Sarah K. Burris
articles.description:
Sen. Tommy Tuberville's (R-AL) blockade appears to be coming to an end, according to an MSNBC report. 
Capitol reporter Ali Vitali said that a group of Republicans were going to take to the Senate floor and force a vote with Democrats to marginalize Tuberville's protest against military promotions that has led to a reduced military readiness for the United States, according to reports.
After a discussion about the absurdity of the protest, host Nicolle Wallace said that she recalled the era when Republicans had to be supportive of the military or they'd be shamed by leaders like Sen. Mitch McConnell (R-KY) and the GOP speaker. 
POLL: Should Trump be allowed to run for office?
Taking to social media, reporter Andrew Desiderio confirmed the reporting, saying that the floor actions will take place tonight, where they will ask for unanimous consent on ending the Tuberville blockade. He said that he was told it would be led by Sen. Dan Sullivan (R-AK). 
The news comes after reports that McConnell threatened Sen. Josh Hawley (R-MO) over his bill to stop corporations from being able to give money to campaigns. McConnell reportedly pointed to Hawley in the caucus lunch and said he wouldn't be there if it wasn't for the money from his Senate Leadership PAC. He went on to threaten any member who supported the bill with a primary. 
It's the first such action heard about from McConnell since he suffered serious injuries from a series of falls and then appeared to freeze at various public press availabilities.
articles.title: Republicans to join Dems in breaking Tuberville's blockade on military promotions: report

articles.description:
What is the greatest threat to peace and stability in the Taiwan Strait? For a growing number of analysts and officials in capitals around the world, the answer is straightforward: An invasion or blockade of Taiwan by the People’s Liberation Army.  Such a fear is not without reason. China’s overt military threats to the island have grown steadily since 2016, when the Chinese government cut off formal contact with Taipei after the inauguration of Tsai Ing-wen as president. China’s military regularly conducts drills in the Taiwan Strait in order to signal resolve and hone its capabilities to seize and control
The post Taiwan’s Most Pressing Challenge Is Strangulation, Not Invasion appeared first on War on the Rocks.
articles.title: Taiwan’s Most Pressing Challenge Is Strangulation, Not Invasion

articles.author: Brian Petit
articles.description:
The grinding Ukrainian military offensive during the summer of 2023 has been a frightful sight for undersized nations fashioning their own defensive strategies against Russia or China. Small nations invaded by numerically superior foes simply do not have the combat power to win a combined arms fight. To nullify this overmatch, out-gunned states require asymmetric options to deter and defend. If deterrence falters and the defense cracks, there are few options to prevent enemy consolidation of control. One irregular option, increasingly present in small-nation defense plans, is the so-called “stay-behind force.”  The purpose of a stay-behind force is plainly stated
The post Should I Stay or Should I Go? Stay-Behind Force Decision-Making appeared first on War on the Rocks.
articles.title: Should I Stay or Should I Go? Stay-Behind Force Decision-Making

US and coalition forces have come under attack at least four more times since the US struck a weapons storage facility in eastern Syria on Wednesday evening, according to a US official. 
 On Wednesday evening, there were two multi-rocket attacks on US and coalition forces at Omar Oil Fields near Mission Support Site Green Village, Syria, and a one-way drone attack on forces at Mission Support Site Euphrates, Syria. 
One of the rocket attacks on Green Village resulted in three US troops suffering minor injuries, the official said.

articles.description:
Business Insider: US government debt is on track to surpass $50 trillion by 2033. That means $5.2 billion is piling up every day. 

 
The US government's debt is on track to surpass $50 trillion by 2033, Bank of America said in a Tuesday note, citing data from the Congressional Budget Office. 
* The US government's public outstanding debt is on track to surpass $50 trillion by 2033. 
* The increase comes out to roughly $5.2 billion every day or $218 million every hour, Bank of America estimated. 
* "Central banks may simply bail out governments in coming years via QE," BofA said. 
US public debt outstanding currently sits at $33.6 trillion and is expected to surge by $20 trillion to $54 trillion within the next decade amid "fiscal excess in the 2020s," Bank of America investment strategist Michael Hartnett said.
"US public debt is... more than the combined GDPs of China, Japan, Germany, and India," he wrote, adding that the outstanding debt is set to surge by $5.2 billion every single day, or $218 million every hour, for the next 10 years.

 
Read more ....

 
Update: US debt to top $50 trillion – BoA (RT).

 
WNU Editor: Interest on the US debt has now crossed $1 trillion a year .... US Debt Interest Bill Rockets Past a Cool $1 Trillion a Year (Bloomberg).
articles.title: Bank Of America Says US Government Debt Is On Track To Surpass $50 Trillion By 2033

articles.description:
Newsweek: White House Delivers Bad News on Ukraine Aid 
White House national security spokesperson John Kirby on Wednesday told reporters that the United States has gone through 96 percent of its funds allocated for Ukraine. 
"Of the total funds that have been provided to Ukraine since the beginning of the war, which is an excess of $60 billion—and that's not just security assistance; that's economic, financial and humanitarian assistance—we've gone through about 96 percent of what's left," Kirby said during a press conference.

Newsweek reached out to the White House via email for comment Wednesday night. 
Read more ....

 
Update: US has used up 96% of funds approved by Congress for Ukraine aid – White House (Ukrainska Pravda)

 
WNU Editor: The media narrative is to blame Congress for not giving more money to Ukraine .... Looming Shutdown Threatens US Aid to Ukraine (VOA). But What is not discussed is that the US President does have a lot of authority to send military aid to a foreign country like Ukraine .... The Not-So-Secret Fund That's Bolstering Ukraine Military Aid: the Presidential Drawdown Authority (Military.com). 
Update #2: Does the US have the money to give away to support the wars in Ukraine and Israel? Maybe not .... Uncle Sam Doesn't Have One Thin Dime For Biden's $106 Billion War Package (Zero Hedge/David Stockman's Contra Corner).
articles.title: White House Says It Has Gone Through 96 Percent Of Its Funds Allocated For Ukraine.

Russian Central Bank

 
RT: Russian central bank estimates how long sanctions will last 
Western restrictions targeting the country’s economy are not expected to be lifted until at least 2027, according to a forecast 

Western restrictions against the Russian economy won’t be lifted within the next several years, the Bank of Russia said in its monetary policy report, released on Tuesday. 
The US and its allies targeted Russia with unprecedented economic sanctions in response to Moscow’s military operation in Ukraine. Due to these restrictions, Russia has effectively been deprived of the ability to conduct international transactions in dollars and euros, and has lost access to the Western banking system. 
Read more ....

 
WNU Editor: I think the Russian Central Bank's forecast of sanctions ending by 2027 is too optimistic. I can easily see these sanctions being in placed for a decade or two after the war in Ukraine is over. In the meantime the EU is planning for even more sanctions .... MOSCOW, November 6. /TASS/. The Anglo-Saxon forces are pushing the Middle East towards a big war, which is leading to a surge in terrorism and millions-strong refugee flows, Russian Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov said.
"We can see the Anglo-Saxons literally pushing the Middle East to the brink of a big war," he pointed out, addressing the Znanie (Knowledge) marathon at the International RUSSIA EXPO.

articles.description:
Nimitz-class carriers at sea
The first-in-class USS Gerald Ford carrier operated alongside the Nimitz-class USS Dwight D. Eisenhower in October amid high tensions in the Middle East.
Credit: Petty Officer 3rd Class Janae Chambers/U.S. Navy

 
Aviation Week: U.S. Navy Considers Extending All Its Nimitz-Class Carriers 
The U.S. Navy’s Nimitz-class carriers are about to turn 50. But given the demand for the carrier air wing and delays to the Nimitz-class replacement—the Ford-class—the USS Nimitz (CVN 68) itself is unlikely to retire as soon as expected. 
The Navy’s fiscal 2023 budget has already called to extend the first-in-class CVN 68, commissioned in 1975, for another deployment cycle instead of decommissioning it in 2025 as previously planned. Service officials say the upcoming budget request could include a final decision on extending the next in the class, the USS Dwight D. Eisenhower, beyond its 2027 projected end-of-service date—though extending just that ship likely will not be enough. 
 Read more ....

 
WNU Editor: The US Navy is also looking to speed-up production of future aircraft carriers .... US Navy mulls timing of new double-carrier award amid Enterprise delay (Defense News).
articles.title: U.S. Navy May Extend All Its Nimitz-Class Carriers For Another Deployment

Reuters: Hezbollah's anti-ship missiles bolster its threat to US navy 
BEIRUT (Reuters) - Powerful Russian anti-ship missiles acquired by Hezbollah give it the means to deliver on its leader's veiled threat against U.S. warships and underline the grave risks of any regional war, sources familiar with the group's arsenal say. 
Hezbollah leader Sayyed Hassan Nasrallah warned Washington last week his group had something in store for the U.S. vessels deployed to the region since war erupted last month between the Palestinian group Hamas and Israel, shaking the wider Middle East. 
Two sources in Lebanon familiar with the Iran-backed group's arsenal say he was referring to Hezbollah's greatly enhanced anti-ship missile capabilities, including the Russian-made Yakhont missile with a range of 300 km (186 miles).

 
Read more ....

 
Update: Hezbollah anti-ship missiles increase threats to US warships: Reuters (Al Mayadeen)

 
WNU Editor: Apparently the video that has been making the rounds on social media that shows Hezbollah's anti-ship missiles is an old one (see video below). But the question still remains. Are Hezbollah's anti-ship missiles a threat to the US Navy? My gut says yes.
articles.title: Are Hezbollah's Anti-Ship Missiles A Threat To The U.S. Navy?

"We can confirm that a U.S. military MQ-9 remotely-piloted aircraft was shot down off the coast of Yemen by Houthi forces," the official said.

CNN: US carries out airstrikes in eastern Syria targeting IRGC and Iranian-backed groups weapons storage facility 
The US military conducted an airstrike on a weapons storage facility in eastern Syria used by Iran’s Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC) and affiliated groups, the Pentagon announced on Wednesday. 
“This precision self-defense strike is a response to a series of attacks against U.S. personnel in Iraq and Syria by IRGC-Quds Force affiliates,” Defense Secretary Lloyd Austin said in a statement. “The President has no higher priority than the safety of U.S. personnel, and he directed today’s action to make clear that the United States will defend itself, its personnel, and its interests.” 
The strike was conducted by two F-15s, Austin said.

articles.description:
DNYUZ/New York Times: ‘If Not Me, Who?’: As Ukraine Seeks Troops, Women Prepare for the Call 
Halyna Vynokur, a clerk in a hardware store in Kyiv, was shouldering a firearm for the first time. Iryna Sychova, a purchasing manager at a department store, disassembled and reassembled the jumble of rods and springs in a Kalashnikov rifle. 
They were among two dozen women who turned out in a forest near Kyiv one recent weekend for a course in firearms and urban combat, training that included shooting rifles, finding booby traps and throwing hand grenades. They were spurred by a sense of duty, they said, realizing they might some day end up on the front lines.

 
Read more ....

 
WNU Editor: Not surprised that Ukraine is going to recruit women to fight in the war. The average age for a soldier in the Ukraine army is 43 years old, and getting older. The Ukraine army is running out of male bodies to fight in this war, and they need new recruits. Since there are a lot of widows and mothers who have lost their sons and loved ones in this war, the Ukraine Army will (I predict) have no trouble tapping into this grief and anger for them to join.
articles.title: Ukraine Wants To Recruit Women To Fight In The War

As war frustrations rise, stalemate tests Zelensky and top general Zaluzhny © Simon Wohlfahrt

 
Washington Post: As war frustrations rise, stalemate tests Zelensky and top general Zaluzhny 
KYIV — After months of heavy losses in a largely stalled counteroffensive against Russia, tension among Ukraine’s senior leaders has spilled awkwardly into the open in recent days — prompting President Volodymyr Zelensky to call for a halt to political infighting. 
“Everyone should be concentrating their efforts right now on defending the country,” Zelensky said Monday in his nightly address. “Put themselves together and do not rest; do not drown in infighting or other issues.” 
He warned that shattered unity could have drastic consequences: “The situation is now the same as it was before — if there is no victory, there will be no country.” 

 
Read more ....

 
WNU Editor: The narrative is that the stalemate is causing this infighting. It is worse than that. This infighting is happening because Ukraine is losing the war.
articles.title: Political Infighting Growing Between Zelensky And His Generals

Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said Monday in his nightly video address it was "utterly irresponsible" to discuss holding elections in Ukraine during a time of war. He called for unity to avoid pointless political discussions.
"We need to recognize that this is a time for defense, a time for battle, upon which the fate of the state and its people depend," he said. "I believe that elections are not appropriate at this time."

Washington CNN  — American troops were attacked an additional eight times since Friday morning by one-way attack drones and rocket barrages in Iraq and Syria as US forces face ramped up attacks by Iranian-backed groups. 
The new incidents – one on Friday afternoon, another on Saturday, five more on Sunday and one on Monday morning – mark a total of at least 38 attacks on US and coalition forces in those two nations since October 17, just days after the start of a bloody war between Israel and Hamas.

The U.S. and its NATO allies served notice Tuesday that they will formally suspend their participation in a 1990 treaty limiting conventional forces in Europe, marking the demise of another landmark arms control agreement. https://t.co/X1T7ZrFLCa pic.twitter.com/qn3IOmBj73
— Geopolitics & Empire (@Geopolitics_Emp) November 7, 2023
  
RT: Russia rules out new arms control deals with NATO

 
There is no point in talks until the US-led bloc adopts more constructive and realistic positions, the Kremlin has said  
The Kremlin has formally withdrawn from a major Cold War-era arms control pact with the NATO military bloc, saying the outdated treaty was already dead for years and had completely “lost touch with reality” in the modern world. 
The Russian Foreign Ministry announced the move on Tuesday, saying the Treaty on Conventional Armed Forces in Europe (CFE) had “finally become history” after prior steps to withdraw, the first of which dates back to 2007. While it originally “played a certain stabilizing role,” the deal was largely ignored by NATO members and thus has “ceased to meet the interests of Russia,” the ministry said.

 
Read more ....

 
WNU Editor: This is the Kremlin's explanation on why they have decided to withdraw from the Conventional Forces in Europe (CFE) treaty .... By criticizing CFE treaty, US wants to shift West’s blame on Russia — diplomat (TASS).
